## Day 1: The End

Maybe there just isn't such a thing as a happy gynaecologist.

You are studying the repair bill on the computer screen, realizing it is almost double of what you have earned so far this month. The clinic hasn't been very busy lately. Fewer and fewer people have the money to pay for a *dentist*, let alone a private gynaecologist. You had to sell your car recently – not that you had the cash for gas, anyway. There's never any cash for anything anymore. This month, there might not be any cash for paying Lydia, even.

Lydia is the lady that brought you up. She has been a nurse in the clinic for ages, originally working with your father, and after he died, with you. You owe her for all that you know about the business side of things, and much more. Still, she has been working practically for free recently.

"Things are falling apart," Lydia told you yesterday. You thought she's talking figuratively, but then she pointed to the cabinet. It was leaning towards a side, one of the legs broken, the paint blistered, top drawer stuck open. She reminded you about the state of the toilet, too, and used the word "disgusting" twice. Other things were falling apart in the waiting room and in your office. That day, you called the cheapest repair service in town. They arrived in under an hour, eyes wide open, smiling, and they quickly took care of everything. Now here's their bill.

Just a couple of years ago, that bill would be worth a portion of your hourly fee. That was when people had the money to pay for things like labiaplasties and 3D ultrasounds. Now, you only see a couple of patients a day, and they are all as broke as you are.

Today, though, is an all-time low. Just one appointment. At least it's a new patient. A young lady called Maria Pruitt.

"A new patient is a good sign," Lydia says when she reminds you about the appointment in the morning. "We haven't had a _new_ patient in, let me see, six months? This could be a turning point. I hope it's a turning point. A new beginning."

What it really is, though, is the beginning of the end. And a spectacular end at that.

But let's not get ahead of ourselves.

